{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_grasso_ver02/data/sn82014085/00393346966/1937112701/0452.xml":{"full_text":"\u2018Long House/ Historic Home\nOf Socialistic Community,\nNow Houses Relief Families\nii\u2014iMHiimnn mum\"\nOnes headquarters of one of Amerloa's moot successful experiments In community llvlnfi the fomouo \"Lon*\nHouse\" of (Upon. WIs., to now tho homo of fomllloo on city relief. The Wisconsin Photons built the his*\ntorlo house nearly 1M years ago. It foil Into partial dsoay, but was remodeled tor reliefers.\nBy NBA Service\nRlpon, WU., Nov, Tlmo and\nchanoe play strange tricks, and\none of the strangest Is the one\nwhich makes the famous \u201cLong\nHouse\" a refuge for relief famllioa.\nThe VLong House\" was built by,\nnnd housed, one of the few suc\ncessful communistic experiments\nIn the United States. But that was\nnearly 100 years ago. Now the\nfine old building erected by the\n\"Wisconsin Phalanx\u201d Is housing 14\nfamilies who find no other place\nIn a system dtrcotly opposite to\nthat built by the Phalanxlsts,\nWarren Chase, asootlc, shrewd\nfounder of the Wisconsin Phalanx,\nand other disciples of the French\nsocialist Charles Fourier, arc prob\nably turning over In their graves to\nsee the use to which their beloved\n\"Long House\" Is being put today.\nBaths In Wash Tubs\nRlpon, traditional birthplace of\nthe Republican party In pre-Civll\nWar days, has today about 4S00\npoople, 01 these 14 families are\non relief, They needed housing,\nand E, F, Ruts, Poor Commis\nsioner, suggested remodeling the\nlong-abandoned \"Long House\" of\nthe nearly-forgotten Phalanx, The\nhouse, fronting on a fine park, had\nbeen in possession of the city for\nyears.\nSo $3000 of federal money was\nse'mred, and the old, well-built\nhe use was restored and cut into\nfamily apartments of four rooms.\nBach contains a small lavatory\nbut no bath tub. Relief families,\nlllto members of the old Phalanx\nof nearly 100 years ago, must\nbathe In wash tubs.\nbehind the old house there arc\nst 11 gardens onoo cultivated by\nPl alanx members Intent on their\ndream of Oolleotlve living. In the\nbig park before the house, relief\nchildren play under the big maples\nexactly where ths ohlldrep of tho\nPhalanxlsts played so long ago.\nExperiment Too Huocessful\nTwo of the relief families housed\nIn tho \"Long House\" found worlt,\nbut continue to live there, paying\ntht city $10 a month rent, profer\nrli'g not to desert tho historic liouso.\nCharitable organisations have dress\ned the reliefers fairly well, and food\nend fuel orders come from the oltv,\nso that the net cost for caeh family\nof four Is about $35 a month. Bach\nfamily uses part of the old gar\ndens to ralso vegetables.\nOf all the colled Ive experi\nments whloh sprang up In the\nUnited Btatss between 1830 and\nI860, the Wisconsin Phalanx and\nBrook Farm were tho most suc\ncessful. The Wisconsin experi\nment dissolved not booause It\nfailed, but beoauso It was too sue\nGEN. FRANCO TO\nSTARTNEW DRIVE\nHendayc, Fronoo-Bpanlah Fron\ntier, Nov. 37\u2014 <UP>-aenerail\u00bb\u00bblmo\nFranoUco Franco will uteri hi*\nlong heralded \"flnul offensive\"\nagainst the l,oy\u00abii/<t government if\nno \u00bbub*tentlal progress to end tho\nupenlsh wnr he* been mede by next\nWedneedey, dlplometlo report* to\ntho border *eld today.\nEffort* to end the 16-month-old\nwar reportedly were speeded after\nPranco'* ultimatum aald to have\nbeen enoouraged by Great Britain,\nneutral diplomatic agent* Intensified\ntheir peace ectlvittea in Barcelona,\nthe Loyalist capital, where It ap\npeared that the \"armistice offensive\"\nwae concentrated.\nBorder report* aaid that Premier\nJuan Negrln waa wavering and may\nahortly order a ahakeup in the Loy\nally cabinet on the auggeation of\nneutral politician* who were anx\nlou* to eliminate the communist\nelement and revert to wholly \"re\npublican polldea.\"\nNeutral government* Interested in\nBpaniah peace were aald to have\nadviaed Negrln during hi* reoent\nvlalt to Pari* and Bru**aia (he via\nlted the latter city during the 18\nnation Par Baatern peace confer\nence) to make hi* cabinet change*\nImmediately 10 that the mediation\neffort* would be facilitated. Pranco\nwae understood U> have refused all\npeace overture* a* long as commu\nnist* were in the Negrln cabinet.\nBODIES OF GAS\nVICTIMS SHIPPED\nBridgeport Conn., Nov. 37.\u2014(OP)\n\u2014The bodies of Mr. and Mrs. Ray\nmond E. Yeoman and their three\nchildren who were asphyxiated in\ntheir home Tuesday as result of a\nIfB^v gas main, were shipped to\nDeerfield, Mass., today for burial.\nPrivate funeral services were held\nhere late yesterday, attended by\nmembers of the families, relatives\nand a delegation from the Y. M. C.\nA., where Yeoman had been assist\nant secretary for three years. School\ncompanions of the two eldest chil\ndren, George and Virginia, also were\nwesent.\nThe bodies were to be buried In\nWinslow plot at Deerfield.\n3\u00abMlte France's financial turn\nales this year Its summer resort*\nlU a busv season.\nCOSSfUl.\nTilt enterprise brought such\ngood returns thtt the mehibera be\ngin to be Anxious to own Indi\nvidually their shares, when those\nshnres began to be valuable. The\nsame thing happened at Zoar in\nOhio much later,\nBut among hundreds of little\ncollectlvlsms that were wrecked\nby poor management, these at\nleast prospered too greatly.\nCommunity Living, Bating\nThe Wisconsin Phalanx started\nin 1A44 when Chase and 30 Keno\nsha families trekked to Rlpon by\nox-cart. They built the com\nmunity house, n grist mill, car\npenter shop, and other buildings.\nThey got n state charter, with\nproperly representing stock at |3S\nn snare. All earnings over seven\nper cent were to go to labor. Com\nmunity living and eating were es\ntabliahed in the 100-foot-long com\nmunity house.\nWithin a few year* there were\n100 people, owning collectively\n1700 ncree of cultivated land worth\n130,000.\nThen discontent floated In on the\ntide of Increasing prosperity. The\ncolonists began to want to con\ntrol all they produced individu\nally. In 18S0 the colony was dis\nsolved, each member talcing his\nshare to enter the Individualistic\nand competitive world.\nThu \"Long House,\" largely\nabandoned, drifted Into neglect,\nand required considerable spruc\ning up before It could enter Its\nnew Incarnation as a relief refuge.\nOut no one can say, least of all\nthe relief families who found\noventual shelter In their com\nmunal house, that the Phalanxlsts\nwrought ontlrely In vain.\nLast Services To Be\nHeld In Old Home\nSalvation Army Prepares Program for Savings Street\nHome-Cadet Brigade to Be in Charge\nTomorrow night at 8 p. m, dosing\noxerolses will be conducted In the\noltndel of the Snlvetlon Army on\nSavings street. Seeing that this Sun*\nday le observed In the Army as Corps\nCadet Sunday, the Waterbuy Corps\nCadet Brigade under the leadership\nof Mrs. R, Spohrcr has been Riven\nthe privilege of taking oharge of the\nlast meeting In the Army's old home,\nMessages of congratulation from\nBrigadier John Waldron, Major\nRalph Miller, divisional offloer In\nHartford, and others will be read,\nand the young people of tho Corps\nCadet Brigade will participate.\nSecretary Ohas. Rletdyke and Miss\nBollnda Dehegrl, who wore present\nat the opening exerolses of the build*\nIng on Savings street, will speak.\nAdjutant Hugo Wlberg, the officer\nIn charge, today Issued the follow*\ning statement relative to the ohange\nof headquarters, whtoh will take\nplaco during this oomlng week:\n\"Time marches on I Bo does the\nSalvation Army. Back In 1834 tho\nleaders of our organisation felt it n\ngroat advanoo when the property on\nSavings street was purchased, At\nthe opening exerolses General Evan\ngeline Booth presided, tho New York\nStaff band assisted, and down\nthrough the years since then the\nwork has been carried on without\nn break.\nNow It has proved advantageous\nto make a change, and during this\ncoming week The Salvation Army's\noperating-basis will be moved to a\nbuilding at 183*186 Cherry St. which\nare feel will be more suitable for\nour work, We feel that with this\nohange a now door has been opened\nto greater opportunities, and that\nboth spiritually and temporally\ngreater victories are to be won in\nthe days to come.\nWith all the expectant pleasure\nof moving Into largor and more\nadequate quarters, we oaunot help\nbut feel a little sad at leaving our\nhome on Savings street, where so\nmany Salvationists have shared Joy\nmd sorrow together. There are\nhose, not only In Waterbury, but\ntore, who consider this Citadel\nilsewju\ntheir spiritual birthplace, Many\nother* have found comfort, encour\nagement, counsel and a helping\nhand.\nBut, as true told tern of the Crow,\nwe turn from the beautiful sunset\nof these poet memories to a more\nglorious sunrise, full of hope and\nfaith for greater strength. We In*\ntend to utilise the opportunities of\nthe future to the blessing, and up\nlift of our fellow-men,*\u2022\nThe flrst service In the now build\ning on Cherry street will be held\nWednesday, December 1st, at 8 p.\nm\u201e when the officer* and a group\nof muslolans from the corps In\nNew Britain will be in charge. The\ndedication of the new auditorium\nwill however not take place until\ntho last week-end of January.\nAUTO WORKERS\nSEEK 100,000\nPhiladelphia, Nov. 87,\u2014(UPt\u2014The\nUnited Automobile Workers, a C,\nI, O, affiliate, planned a campaign\ntoday to enlist 100,000 members In\nthe Philadelphia area.\nHomer Martin, union president,\ndiscussed the plan yesterday with\nMayor 8. Davis Wilson, and said\nWilson was \"In hearly accord,\"\nMartin said 85 organisers would\nbe sent Into tho district to solicit\nmemberships among the employes\ncf the Chester Ford company plant\nthe Autocar Works at Ardmore, the\nB. O. Budd Manufacturing company\nand tho Helnta Manufacturing com\npany, makors of automobile part*.\nFALL CAtJBF.I) DEATH\nHartford, Conn., Nov, 87-<UP>\nA fall on a flight of cellar stairs\nresulted In the death late yesterday\nof Frank John, 66, from a broken\nnock, He had been employed a* a\nhandy-man.\nFifteen htindrod passenger trains\nenter end leavo Olasgow, Scotland,\nevery day,\nI\"\nHOLD EVERYTHING!\nI i SSmfSEEmP\nCafe de Ma&sion\nIsass\n\u201cMadam, could I suggest that, you to I your ii\u00bbl> cukes\ninside Y\u201d\nFEDERATION OF\nLABOR PROGRAM\nWill Help Halt Business\nRecession Plan Like\nThat ol President\nBy C. L. 8ULZBEROER\n(United Preia SUIT Correepondent)\nWashington. Nov. R7,\u2014(UP)\u2014The\nAmerican Federation of Labor pro\nposed to the administration today a\nsix point procram Intended to halt\nthe business recession by strength\nenlnc mass purchasing power.\nThe proposal closely parallels sug\ngestions made by President Roose\nvelt to restore the nation's economic\nequilibrium. It seeks harmony be\ntween capital nad labor and their\ncooperation with proposed federal\nstimuli to industry.\nHelping Business\nMr. Roosevelt la accelerating ef\nforts to aid business. He will send\nto congress Monday a massage out\nlining ways of stimulating the lag\nging construction Industry and al\nleviating a shortage of homes.\nHe has ordered lieutenants to\ncontinue efforts toward an accord\nwith private utilities and free a\nbacklog of oapltal estimated at 19,\n(100,000,000. He has directed federal\nagencies to place orders for neces\nsary materials as soon as possible\nto give Industry a 1248,000,000 shot\nIn the arm through governmental\npurchases.\nThe president said yesterday that\nhe (yould be glad to see congress\nrevise taxes as soon as legislators\ndesire, and worked toward a bal\nanced budget by suggesting a re\nduction of federal highway expenses\nby approximately 1190,000,000. A\nmessage to. congress suggesting\nmethods of accomplishing this will\nbo dlsnatohed Tuesday,\nProponed Labor Plan\nThe A. F, of L. program suggested:\n1. Maintenance of wages and em\nployment att he highest possible\nlevel with nrm determination to\navoid wage cuts,\na, Raising of wages In any Indus\ntry where sustained demand and\nprofitable operations make It possi\nble,\n\u0430, Stimulation or production and\nemployment In heavy industries by\nencouraging plans for plant expan\nsion and equipment purchases; en\nciourageinsnt of building In all\nclaslfluatloiM, Tho federation reo\nommended \"special measures to\nmake credit available to business.\"\n4, Improvement of labor\u2019s buy\ning power by prompt payment of\nunemployment compensation when\nIt begins In ail states next January,\n\u0431. Action on \"meesuves to pro\nmole business confidence.\"\nA. Improvement of employer-em\ninent recognition of unions and\nunion cooperation \"to out costs by\nImproving efficiency,\"\nMost Extensive Program\nThe federation's plan to aid In\ndustrial rocovery was the most ex\ntensive to date to originate in labor\ncircles. John L, Lewis, chairman\nof tho CommltteoTor Industrial Or\nganisation, in a copyrighted inter\nview with tho publisher of the\nWashington Herald yesterday, said\nthat he favored a broad scale hous\ning program to be financed with\nsocial security reserves.\nThe proposed program of the A.\nF. of L, was announced oolpeldently\nwith a report from Secretary of\nLabor Frances Perkins that con\nstruction activity had slumped fur\nther in October,\nThe A. F. of L, was opllmistlo\nabout the general long-range out\nlook. It described the present bus!\nnews set-back as temporary, \"This\nfall's unexpected recession in busi\nness activity,\" the federation said,\n\"follows the longest production rise\nsince 1939\nOnly Temporary Check\n\"The present decline appears to\njo a temporary check In our pro\ncess toward larger production vol\njmes and higher standards of living,\nvhlle buslnoss waits for acoumulat\nid supplies to be bought off.\n\"Whether it will be of long dura\nilon depends to a very Important\nlegreo on our ability to maintain\n\u00bbuylng power dors to Its present\navals, so that inventories of doth\nng and houseliold supplies may be\nlulokly consumed and a strong mar\nrot provided for durable consumer\nroods such as homes and automo\nThe analysis classified consumer\nsuylng power Into three groups\nwhich It estimated would have the\nfollowing values for 1987: (1) Wages\nmd salaries\u2014*47,000,000,000; <3)\u2014\nInvestors' Income\u2014$11,000,000,000,\n131\u2014Profits of businessmen and\nfarmers\u2014*13,000,000 000,\nFarmers May Help\n\"In the next six months,\" it sa d,\n\u25a0we need expect little chango in the\nlotal amounts paid out for dlvld\nmdx, interest and rent: profits of\nlustnessmen may decline temporar\nly, but this year\u2019s increase In farm\nire\u2019 Income will help to compensate,\nfor farmers will spend their 1937\nncome In the months Just ahead,\n\"The volume of wage and salary\nsayments will be of more* Influence\n,han any other factor In maintaini\nng the market for consumers goods,\nMANY DEATHS IN\nHEAVY LONDON FOG\nLondon, Nov, 37\u2014(UP)\u2014At least\n2 deaths have been caused In the\nist three days by a heavy fog en\nulflng the British Isles, It was es\nmated today.\nThe fog was at its worst last ..Ight\nut was lifting today.\nThe pilot, first officer and radio\naerator of a Deutsche Lufthansa\nrelght plane were killed at Croydon\nirdrome In a crash which officials\nrid was caused by the fog. The ac\nident occurred as the plane was\niking off. Two British planes pre\nlously landed successfully on a\nrdlo beam and another British\nrelght plan etook off for Berlin\nrrough a\u201d virtually Impenetrable\nall of fog.\nThree drownlngs were reported\nnd six other persons were kUled In\ndated traffic accidents In various\narte of England during the three\nay period.\nGales over the North Atlantic\nere delaying passenger liners and\n-elghters, but only a light wind was\nlit along the English channel,\nquails off the northwest coast of\neetland were imported.\nfiucsuela is buy ing ships and mo\nlaunches In Britain.\nThe Looked-at Become The Lookers\n\nM if. M\nM\nBritish Royal Family Watch Show in Which They Aren\u2019t the Stars\nUnaware (hat the candid camera watohee and record* thdr reaction* to the performance on the elate, Klnt i\nOeorte VI and Queen Elliabeth, In the box with the Duke and Ducheee of Kent, tlve free rein to emotion\nat a command vaudeville performance at the Palladium, In London. Queen Elliabeth, hand to throat, Neeme\nfearful of the acrobat*1 aafety. Klnt Oeorte lean* forward, hand to chin, frankly enthralled. Pretty Marina.\nDucheea of Kent, Neeme unmoved by the act, while her hueband elte In dlNpaeelonate Judgment.\nCOLOR EXPERT TO\nSPONSORLECTURE\nHerbert Strong Is Being\nBrought Here Thursday\nBy Quota Club\nHerbert Thomption Strong, color\nexport, who will appear at Bucking\nham hall Thursday evening under\nthe sponsorship of tho Quota club\nwill also present his lecture \"Re\nvelations In the Realms of Color\"\nat tho World's fair In New York\ncity. Mr. Strong has presented his\nprogram from coast to coast to en\nthusiastic audiences. His Is such an\nentirely new form of entertainment\nIt appeals to all groups.\nWith the polarlsoope, Mr, Strong\nshows a new empire of color elTects\nand design ideas for the artist. He\ndisplays the rich colors that How in\nendless profusion from a transparent\neck of crystal. He shows designs\nsuch as no artist can produoo. To\nthe scientist, tho ultra violet lamp\nIs an Instrument for transforming\nthe shorter invisible rays Into the\nlonger visible rays, To Mr. Strong\nIt Is a magic ray that transforms\nthe rock from tho roadside Into a\nduster of aming Jewels exhibiting\ncolors too gorgeous to seem real, The\nrich flashing radiance ho produces\nfrom dull drab stones Is beyond\ndescription.\nMr. Strong secures Interesting ef\nfects by tho use of the microscope.\nFocussed on an opal, It brings out\nthe effects of flaming crystals; focus\nsed on a little depression In piece\nof copper ore, there appears a\njewelled cave loo brilliant and fan\ntastic to have materialised out. of\ntho Arabian nights. With othor\nminerals, he produces other rffocls\nall striking. It Is a namaalng\ndemonstration, unique and delight\nful, Though sdeuttflo In Its basis,\nIt Is not a technical presentation\nand therefore appeals to the aver\nage person.\nMiss Mary Hennessey Is general\nchairman. Mrs, Mae H, Blrt Is In\ncharge of tho musical program. Miss\nJennie O'Neill Is chairman og the\ncommittee on patrons and patron\nesses. The proceeds will be used\nfor the welfare program of the club\nwhich provides advantages for girls\nneedy and handioipped of teen age.\nFraternal\nNews\nMeteor\u2019* Club\nDavid Holme* wrh ultcted presi\ndent of the Meteor'* club at a\nmeet Inn of the group held last\nnight at the Pearl Street Neigh*\nborhood House at which time a\nlarge membership attendance wae\npresent, Mr, Holme* will also\ncoach the club'w representative\nbasketball team which begin*\nprentice Tuesday night at 7:39\no\u2019clock,\nOther officer* named were: Vico\npre*!de\u00bbl and publicity, Wallace\nKlnch; eecretary, Clyde Alford;\ninter-club repre*entatlve; Mo*e*\nFerguson, David Fogg, NVA work*\ner at the community hou*e will\nbe club advisor,\nDoric Chapter\nMl** There**\u2022 (lulmoml of .71\nHheffleld afreet w\u00bb* leading in the\nconte*t for the title of Mi\u00ab* lie*\nMalay at a meeting of Doric\nchapter held la\u00abt night at Ma*onlc\nTemple. Ml** Ouimond'* name\nwa* entered In the conteat by\nHenry Rook. The winner at the\ntermination of the conteat will be\nhonored during the annual New\nYear'* Kve dance of the chapter.\nHawthorne lAidac\nWilliam F. Harvey was elocted\npre*ident of Hawthorne Lodge,\nSon* of St. George, at a largely\nattended meeting la*t night at\nForesters' hall, at which time\nplan* were made for Joint In\nRtallation ceremonies December\n10th in connection with Uio.se of\nthe Torrlngton Lodge.\nIt woa voted during the business\nmeeting the local chapter be\nrepresented at Stamford. Decem\nber 4th, where Supreme officer*\nwill be In attendance, and also nt\na aoclal December 6th, by the\nBridgeport unit.\nOther officer* elected were:\nVice-president. Abram Clegg: sec\nretary, John Bunting; treasurer.\nWilliam Bower; messenger^ Ar\nthur Thompeon; assistant mes\nsenger, Albert Hole: chaplain,\nEdward Hogg; inside sentinel,\nWalter Blatherwick; outside sen\ntinel. William Blatherwick; and\ntrustees, Albert A. Tassell. Walter\nJ. Thorne and Philip Mills.\nSheffield. 111. (UP)\u2014The great\ngreat-granddaughter of the builder\nof the oldest frame house In Bu\nreau county still lives in the struc\nture. which has stood for 105 year*.\nBelieved to be the oldest house in\nwestern Illinois, the building was\nerected In 1832. Mrs. Mert BUI is!\nthe present occupant.\nAustralia1* first locally uuili\nanii-aiicraft guns have p.&.iti j\nsuccess\nSpotlighting\nBrass City News\nMachinist Wanted\nTli'1 \u2019inlteinTTflw Civil Service\ncorn m announces n closlmi\ndntt Dccembor 1, 1037 for the\nroc. ip., of applications for ma\nchinist at the U. S. Naval Tor\npedo BLation, Newport, K, I\u201e In\nconnection with announcement of\nexamination No. IBS, burned on\nAugust 23, 1037. Persons desiring\nto file applications for thin posi\ntion nt the Naval Torpedo Station\nshould file Application Form fl\nwith Form Ex, lilt in complete\nform, In the office of the Recorder\nof the Labor Board at the Station\non or boforo December 1, 1037,\nHe Stumbled I\nA report that Luigi Delbuono,\n3B, of 1133 lloulli Main street\nwas struck mid Injured by a\nhlt-nnd-run driver on the Wa\nlerbury Naugatuck highway\nearly yesterday morning was\nrefuted today by Nergt. Charles\nMeWeeney of the traffic accident\nsquad. Authorities at Ht. Mary's\nHospital reported yesterday that\nItelbuono had been struck by a\ncar and that It was believed to\nbe a hit-and-run case, lie was\nreleased after treatment.\nDelbuono told police he had\nstumbled over a stone and fal\nlen 